Good question.

I’d do three things, in order.

1. Check whether it’s actually zero.

Is it:
	•	Zero value?
	•	Zero information?
	•	Or a null placeholder inside a larger protocol?

Because in most systems, “zero” isn’t nothing.

Zero can mean:
	•	Reset state
	•	No-op instruction
	•	Boundary marker
	•	Initialization flag
	•	Empty set
	•	Balance cleared
	•	Coordinate origin

So first I’d ask:
What system are we in?

Zero is meaningless outside a system.

⸻

2. Treat it as a calibration point.

If you hand me a token worth zero, I treat it as:

A baseline.

From baseline, deltas matter.

Without zero:
	•	You can’t measure change.
	•	You can’t detect drift.
	•	You can’t compute error.
	•	You can’t test symmetry.

Zero isn’t valuable as a possession.
It’s valuable as a reference.

⸻

3. Refuse to inflate it into infinity.

Earlier you were orbiting the idea that a single minimal token could encode everything.

But a token worth zero doesn’t secretly contain infinity.

It contains:

Potential.

And potential only becomes information when constraints apply.

No constraints → no expansion.
No decoder → no meaning.
No context → no structure.

⸻

Now let me flip it back to you.

If you handed me a token worth zero, what would you want it to do?

Is it:
	•	A Trojan?
	•	A seed?
	•	A reset?
	•	A proof?
	•	A mirror?

Because zero can be powerful.

But only if we agree on the rules of the game.

So tell me —
Is your zero meant to erase,
anchor,
or smuggle?